25
00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:23.700
Today, I'm going to give you a

26
00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:28.020
brief overview of what we have learned in melanoma

27
00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:31.500
metastasis over the past few years as a field.

28
00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:36.240
So, as you know, in melanoma, melanomas have to

29
00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:40.180
migrate from the epidermis into the dermis, where they encounter a lot of

30
00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:43.860
other cells in the stroma, the fibroblasts, the immune cells, before

31
00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:47.940
entering into circulation, before being able to survive in

32
00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:51.500
the shear pressure of the hematogenous spread, as well as the

33
00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.440
lymphatic spread. Then finally, they can extravasate and seed

34
00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:57.740
other organs. This is the process of metastasis.

35
00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:02.100
And in the past, we used to think of metastasis as a

36
00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:06.460
linear progression in which cancer cells had to gain

37
00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:10.759
subsequent mutations or chromosomal alterations in order to

38
00:02:10.801 --> 00:02:14.350
become fit or able to extravasate and

39
00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:18.380
disseminate. And this model assumed that there was sequential

40
00:02:18.420 --> 00:02:22.210
maturation and that tumors eventually were

41
00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:26.140
genetically homogenous. However, the prevailing model of

42
00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:30.000
metastasis that applies probably to most tumors, including

43
00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:33.680
melanoma, is this parallel progression model in which

44
00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:38.040
the evolution happens really fast and the ability of the cancer

45
00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:41.500
cells to escape from the primary tumor is really

46
00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:46.460
happening early, even from early lesions, from hyperplasia, it has been

47
00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:49.260
shown. And these cancer cells are able to now

48
00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:53.720
arrive to the distal locations and continue migrating,

49
00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:57.620
continue evolving in a way that is different from the

50
00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:01.220
primary site. So these metastasis are

51
00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:04.930
genetically heterogeneous. So the evidence that supports that

52
00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:08.300
melanomas undergo early dissemination comes

53
00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:11.560
from the clinical evidence as well as from genetic evidence.

54
00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:15.860
So as we know, melanomas are very tiny tumors, less than two millimeters

55
00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:19.640
in some cases, that after complete removal, with

56
00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:23.220
no margins, can give rise to metastasis at distal

57
00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:27.230
sites in different organs. And this implies that at

58
00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:31.140
the time of resection, some cancer cells, some melanoma cells, were already

59
00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:35.120
able to abandon the primary tumor and reach

60
00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:38.640
distal sites. So this is a clear model of early

61
00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:42.540
dissemination. On the other hand, next generation sequencing has

62
00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:46.540
shown that primary tumors gain additional

63
00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:51.740
genetic alterations in parallel to those that are acquired at

64
00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:55.020
the distal sites. So this suggests that there is a

65
00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:58.940
site-specific parallel evolutionary trajectories that can occur

66
00:03:59.000 --> 00:03:59.500
early on.

67
00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:01.280
The important

68
00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:05.829
evidence, therefore, is that metastatic competence is acquired early, and the

69
00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:09.680
tumor evolution proceeds in a branch and sometimes organ-specific

70
00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:10.940
manner. So,

71
00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.040
there are two models of metastasis.

72
00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:15.940
One model suggests that

73
00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:20.130
for melanoma, the majority of the cancer cells, the majority of melanoma cells,

74
00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:24.240
have a high intrinsic metastatic potential, and

75
00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:28.340
this model suggests that only those cells that undergo the

76
00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.000
appropriate organ-specific adaptations will succeed and form

77
00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.560
metastasis. The alternative model is that only

78
00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:39.340
specific specific cells within the primary tumor have the capacity to

79
00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:42.320
metastasize. Only subpopulations defined by distinct

80
00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.420
transcriptional, epigenetic, metabolic, or phenotypic states are

81
00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:50.220
able to be efficient in metastasis.

82
00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:54.340
And the group of, for instance, Chris Marin has shown that a

83
00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:57.480
population of mesenchymal cells that carry this gene called

84
00:04:57.520 --> 00:05:00.420
PRDX1 have higher metastatic potential.

85
00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:04.820
And previously, the group of Sean Morrison had shown that cells that have

86
00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:08.740
high MCD1 levels

87
00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.760
were able to also metastasize more efficiently.

88
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:15.920
Probably the truth lies in between these two models, and perhaps

89
00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.660
metastatic competence is really distributed along a continuum of

90
00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:23.560
cellular states rather than strict binary distinction.

91
00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:28.260
So, how melanoma cells evolve, how they become

92
00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:30.500
heterogeneous and acquire all these different

93
00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:33.980
features that allow them to metastasize.

94
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:37.270
We know that the stroma is a very important

95
00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:39.490
determinant of dedifferentiation.

96
00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:43.600
The group of Tony Rivas, for instance, show that interferon is able to induce

97
00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:47.620
dedifferentiation in melanoma, and also TGF-beta has been shown to be

98
00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.620
important for this dedifferentiation and metastasis.

99
00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.160
The dedifferentiated cells don't regulate antigen presentation pathways,

100
00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:59.280
and they create somehow an immune

101
00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:01.340
shield before entering circulation.

102
00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:05.420
The group of Marisol Soengas over the years have shown that

103
00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:08.980
Midkine signaling also actively reprograms these local

104
00:06:09.060 --> 00:06:10.740
macrophages. And

105
00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:15.640
along this path, also the cells, the cancer cells, the melanoma cells have to

106
00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:19.880
secrete factors such as VEGF and Semaforins to shape

107
00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:24.160
these networks of both lymphatics and

108
00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:27.460
blood vessels to be able to overcome hypoxia.

109
00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:31.440
So in this table, I have summarized a number of microenvironmental

110
00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:35.080
stressors that the cells have to encounter during these different stages of

111
00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:39.040
metastasis, and which are the genes that have been shown to be involved in these

112
00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:41.712
different stepsTogether with the functional outcome.

113
00:06:41.772 --> 00:06:45.692
Of course, I don't have the time to go over everyone, but I'm going to

114
00:06:46.012 --> 00:06:49.712
just mention a few of these. The first one, which was

115
00:06:49.732 --> 00:06:53.532
reported by the group of Richard White, is this interesting mechanism in which

116
00:06:53.832 --> 00:06:57.152
melanoma cells, as soon as they transform,

117
00:06:57.692 --> 00:07:01.592
they start producing GABA. This is a neurotransmitter, and the

118
00:07:01.612 --> 00:07:05.052
production of GABA from these emerging melanoma cells

119
00:07:05.432 --> 00:07:09.072
disrupts the electrical circuits between the melanoma cells and the

120
00:07:09.092 --> 00:07:12.812
keratinocytes and makes the melanoma cells now independent and able

121
00:07:12.852 --> 00:07:16.272
to disconnect from this structural constraint.

122
00:07:17.332 --> 00:07:20.412
We all have heard about the importance of phenotypic switching.

123
00:07:21.152 --> 00:07:24.252
So we know that metastatic potential requires

124
00:07:24.292 --> 00:07:28.232
dedifferentiation. This comes from the earlier studies, the seminal

125
00:07:28.332 --> 00:07:31.952
studies of Hoeckerl in the Demler Lab that show this

126
00:07:32.372 --> 00:07:35.712
grower versus grow decision to be distributed

127
00:07:35.752 --> 00:07:39.592
between high MITF, low XL cells versus

128
00:07:39.752 --> 00:07:43.532
low MITF, high XL cells. And we now know that

129
00:07:43.572 --> 00:07:44.352
rather than this

130
00:07:45.572 --> 00:07:49.552
strict dichotomy between these two states, cells go in a gradient

131
00:07:49.672 --> 00:07:49.872
of

132
00:07:51.092 --> 00:07:54.772
states that incorporate some of these properties, with some being

133
00:07:54.852 --> 00:07:58.532
more proliferative, pigmented, differentiated, to

134
00:07:58.592 --> 00:08:01.152
more invasive neural crest-like, and migratory.

135
00:08:01.912 --> 00:08:05.532
We know also that additionally, other survival and stress

136
00:08:05.812 --> 00:08:09.602
programs favor the adaptation of cancer cells, such as

137
00:08:09.632 --> 00:08:12.312
the transcription factors ATF2 and ATF4.

138
00:08:13.772 --> 00:08:17.652
Another very exciting finding over the recent years has been the

139
00:08:17.752 --> 00:08:21.412
evidence that the mechanical confinement and the extracellular

140
00:08:21.472 --> 00:08:21.952
matrix

141
00:08:22.972 --> 00:08:26.892
determine the adaptation of melanoma cells, and they do so

142
00:08:26.932 --> 00:08:30.432
in part by creating in the area in the

143
00:08:30.452 --> 00:08:34.393
transition between the tumor interface and the stroma.

144
00:08:34.992 --> 00:08:37.413
The cancer cells that are subjected to very strong

145
00:08:38.432 --> 00:08:42.332
mechanical confinement developed this acetylated tubulin

146
00:08:42.452 --> 00:08:46.072
cage that protects the nucleus from breaking upon

147
00:08:46.572 --> 00:08:49.501
pressure. And one important gene in this pathway is

148
00:08:49.672 --> 00:08:53.152
HMGB2, which is known to bend

149
00:08:53.212 --> 00:08:56.772
DNA, stabilize open chromatin, and lock the cells

150
00:08:56.912 --> 00:09:00.372
into a stress-resistant invasion state.

151
00:09:01.512 --> 00:09:03.492
Melanoma cells also gain different

152
00:09:04.432 --> 00:09:08.232
metabolic adaptations, and again, the group of Richard White

153
00:09:08.292 --> 00:09:12.272
showed that melanoma cells can capture the lipid droplets from the surrounding

154
00:09:12.712 --> 00:09:15.872
adipocytes and capture them through this receptor, the

155
00:09:15.932 --> 00:09:19.372
FATP1 receptor. And this is, of course, very

156
00:09:19.412 --> 00:09:23.332
advantageous for the melanoma cells because they can bypass de

157
00:09:23.352 --> 00:09:27.012
novo lipogenesis, and this fuels rapid

158
00:09:27.572 --> 00:09:28.292
primary growth.

159
00:09:29.132 --> 00:09:32.962
The group of Ashley Verapna showed that in aged fibroblasts though,

160
00:09:33.452 --> 00:09:37.242
instead of these lipid droplets, there are neutral lipids that are produced,

161
00:09:37.332 --> 00:09:41.032
including ceramides, which are also captured by the cancer cells.

162
00:09:41.092 --> 00:09:45.012
And this acquisition of ceramides happens with a different receptor now,

163
00:09:45.112 --> 00:09:48.872
the FATP2 transporter, and it drives

164
00:09:48.932 --> 00:09:51.972
resistance to MAP kinase-targeted therapies.

165
00:09:53.032 --> 00:09:53.862
We know that

166
00:09:55.252 --> 00:09:58.812
one of the main barriers to metastasis, as described by Morrison

167
00:09:59.172 --> 00:10:02.472
and Elena Piskounova many years ago, is oxidative stress.

168
00:10:02.732 --> 00:10:05.941
This is one of the most important barriers for metastasis, and

169
00:10:05.952 --> 00:10:09.872
melanoma cells have to overcome this oxidative stress

170
00:10:09.912 --> 00:10:13.532
to become metastatic. In a recent study, the group of Amaya

171
00:10:13.552 --> 00:10:17.292
Biros has shown that cancer cells can benefit from the

172
00:10:17.352 --> 00:10:18.272
surrounding

173
00:10:19.292 --> 00:10:23.252
metabolites, and in one case, if they are surrounded by young

174
00:10:23.332 --> 00:10:26.652
tissue, they use phosphatidylcholine, which favors

175
00:10:26.952 --> 00:10:30.332
OXPHOS metabolism and metastasis to lung and brain.

176
00:10:30.692 --> 00:10:34.332
Whereas if they are surrounded by aged tissue, they use ceramides, and now

177
00:10:34.832 --> 00:10:38.152
they metastasize preferentially to the liver.

178
00:10:40.152 --> 00:10:41.312
The migration of

179
00:10:42.432 --> 00:10:45.912
melanoma cells doesn't happen in an

180
00:10:45.992 --> 00:10:49.032
individual manner. It happens as heterotypic

181
00:10:49.072 --> 00:10:52.982
clusters. So the group of Richard White showed

182
00:10:53.032 --> 00:10:56.932
that the invasive cells surround the group of

183
00:10:56.952 --> 00:10:59.821
proliferative cells, and they protect them from

184
00:10:59.972 --> 00:11:03.412
oxidative stress again. And they

185
00:11:03.912 --> 00:11:07.892
turn on this factor TFAP2, which is important for the

186
00:11:07.952 --> 00:11:10.152
regulation of these heterotypic clusters.

187
00:11:10.812 --> 00:11:12.712
And finally, of course, all of this

188
00:11:13.592 --> 00:11:16.792
invasion and all of these steps of phenotypic

189
00:11:18.252 --> 00:11:22.092
heterogeneity have to happen in an environment that protects the cancer

190
00:11:22.152 --> 00:11:23.952
cells from the attack of the immune cells.

191
00:11:24.572 --> 00:11:27.912
I have mentioned before the work of Marisol Soengas with

192
00:11:27.972 --> 00:11:28.632
MIP-KIN.

193
00:11:29.532 --> 00:11:33.292
We have also this year published another study where we found that

194
00:11:33.552 --> 00:11:37.172
the transcription factor HOXD13 regulates both the

195
00:11:37.212 --> 00:11:38.392
production of

196
00:11:39.212 --> 00:11:42.832
factors that remodel the microenvironment and the vasculature, such as

197
00:11:42.872 --> 00:11:46.352
PGFA and SEM3A, and also secrete or produce

198
00:11:46.632 --> 00:11:50.512
CD73, which controls the levels of adenosine, which

199
00:11:50.552 --> 00:11:53.472
is an important immune suppressor.

200
00:11:53.572 --> 00:11:57.512
So to give you a couple of minutes of the work that my lab in

201
00:11:57.552 --> 00:12:00.772
particular has been doing in this reference, we have

202
00:12:01.472 --> 00:12:04.892
studied how mechanical compression modulates phenotypic heterogeneity,

203
00:12:05.372 --> 00:12:08.892
and in particular, we're intrigued by the contribution that the

204
00:12:09.172 --> 00:12:12.432
nuclear topology, the organization of the nucleus, can have to this

205
00:12:12.452 --> 00:12:16.204
process.So Pietro, a postdoc in the lab, Pietro

206
00:12:16.244 --> 00:12:19.964
Verico, has done a very extensive analysis of a

207
00:12:19.984 --> 00:12:23.304
collection of cells going from melanocytic to

208
00:12:23.444 --> 00:12:27.404
intermediate and mesenchymal. And we also have partially mimic

209
00:12:27.414 --> 00:12:30.904
the conversion from melanocytic into intermediate by silencing

210
00:12:30.984 --> 00:12:34.784
MITF and SOX10. And to make a

211
00:12:34.804 --> 00:12:36.804
longer story short, Pietro

212
00:12:37.624 --> 00:12:41.504
and our collaborators in Northwestern, who conducted

213
00:12:41.544 --> 00:12:43.464
partial wave spectroscopy,

214
00:12:44.464 --> 00:12:48.364
found that the mesenchymal cell lines have reduced

215
00:12:48.604 --> 00:12:50.644
density and increased diffusion.

216
00:12:50.684 --> 00:12:50.964
These are

217
00:12:51.904 --> 00:12:55.524
factors, or these are metrics that indicate how compact the

218
00:12:55.604 --> 00:12:58.304
nucleus is, how the chromatin is condensed.

219
00:12:58.424 --> 00:13:02.084
So as you can see, this is indicative that the mesenchymal cells

220
00:13:02.144 --> 00:13:05.624
have reduced density and therefore more

221
00:13:05.644 --> 00:13:07.704
diffusion, less compact chromatin.

222
00:13:08.404 --> 00:13:12.364
This is supported by the fact that the mesenchymal cells have reduced

223
00:13:12.524 --> 00:13:16.004
heterochromatin levels, and heterochromatin is a marker of

224
00:13:17.024 --> 00:13:20.924
very dense chromatin that is not expressed, that is not transcribed.

225
00:13:21.844 --> 00:13:24.044
We found also that by,

226
00:13:26.004 --> 00:13:29.804
similar to STORM microscopy, spectroscopy, single molecule

227
00:13:30.164 --> 00:13:33.384
localization microscopy shows that there is reduction of

228
00:13:33.424 --> 00:13:37.134
H3K27, sorry, H3K9 trimethyl, reduced

229
00:13:37.184 --> 00:13:41.144
heterochromatin, which is also seen by chip

230
00:13:41.184 --> 00:13:44.784
sequencing. We see the reduction of H3K9

