00:14:55.464 --> 00:14:58.764
MITF and SOX10, these melanocytic markers, and no

251
00:14:58.824 --> 00:15:02.334
upregulation of the mesenchymal markers, axle of

252
00:15:02.384 --> 00:15:05.924
EGFR. So we see that just simply the

253
00:15:05.964 --> 00:15:08.564
passing through these very narrow pores

254
00:15:08.624 --> 00:15:12.184
induces the repression of

255
00:15:12.204 --> 00:15:16.184
heterochromatin and also reduces the density of

256
00:15:16.244 --> 00:15:17.564
the nucleus. So,

257
00:15:18.944 --> 00:15:22.924
when we now take cells from the upper part before the

258
00:15:23.284 --> 00:15:26.964
constriction and cells that have undergone this constriction, and now

259
00:15:27.004 --> 00:15:30.784
we inject them intracardially to examine their

260
00:15:31.104 --> 00:15:35.024
metastatic potential, we see that the ones that were on the

261
00:15:35.044 --> 00:15:36.024
other side, the ones that

262
00:15:37.564 --> 00:15:41.144
had undergone this constriction, had significantly

263
00:15:41.204 --> 00:15:43.924
increased liver metastasis. So,

264
00:15:45.104 --> 00:15:48.694
to summarize this part, we have seen that migration through

265
00:15:48.694 --> 00:15:52.384
these narrow channels does not just select for aggressive cells.

266
00:15:52.544 --> 00:15:56.384
It actually confers increased metastatic potential without

267
00:15:56.464 --> 00:15:58.664
altering the proliferative capacity of the cells.

268
00:15:59.184 --> 00:16:02.824
And this level of squeezing or compression induces

269
00:16:02.944 --> 00:16:06.924
changes in the melanocytic cells that are reminiscent of the changes that

270
00:16:06.944 --> 00:16:10.484
we see in mesenchymal cells, like reduced heterochromatin,

271
00:16:10.784 --> 00:16:14.104
reduced nuclear density, increased diffusion.

272
00:16:14.574 --> 00:16:18.564
And this is important because then we have to think that mechanical forces that

273
00:16:18.584 --> 00:16:20.384
the cells are undergoing, their

274
00:16:21.304 --> 00:16:24.764
pathway to metastasis, are not just passive constraints.

275
00:16:24.824 --> 00:16:28.484
They are actively pushing differentiated

276
00:16:28.524 --> 00:16:31.754
cells towards a more mesenchymal-like structure,

277
00:16:32.324 --> 00:16:35.744
and this endows much more physical nuclear

278
00:16:35.784 --> 00:16:39.524
deformability. So it's a win-win for the cancer cells in the sense that

279
00:16:39.584 --> 00:16:39.984
now they

280
00:16:41.704 --> 00:16:44.364
have more deformable and flexible nuclei.

281
00:16:45.644 --> 00:16:49.124
I don't have the time to present all this data, but we have shown that in the

282
00:16:49.184 --> 00:16:50.164
conversion from the

283
00:16:51.284 --> 00:16:55.264
melanocytic to mesenchymal cells, the nucleus gets relaxed, the chromatin is much

284
00:16:55.284 --> 00:16:59.204
more relaxed, and CTCF, which is the guardian

285
00:16:59.344 --> 00:17:00.484
of the TADS, of the

286
00:17:01.664 --> 00:17:04.964
transcriptional domains, is now moved from these boundaries

287
00:17:05.364 --> 00:17:09.004
to the promoters of mesenchymal genes

288
00:17:09.305 --> 00:17:12.423
cooperating with AP1. So we have demonstrated that

289
00:17:13.224 --> 00:17:16.864
this mesenchymal state gives two advantages to the cells.

290
00:17:16.924 --> 00:17:20.815
One is physical. They have much more deformability, and also

291
00:17:21.085 --> 00:17:25.045
transcriptional. This facilitates the regulation, the changes in gene regulation by

292
00:17:25.065 --> 00:17:28.804
the formation of new hubs. We have done a screen, so that I don't have the time to

293
00:17:28.824 --> 00:17:32.444
present, but you can look at the preprint to demonstrate that

294
00:17:32.504 --> 00:17:36.264
now these cells have new chromatin hubs

295
00:17:36.444 --> 00:17:38.064
that contribute to metastasis.

296
00:17:39.264 --> 00:17:42.964
And now I'm going to move to the next question, is like why

297
00:17:43.644 --> 00:17:46.964
or is really the differentiation or the acquisition of a

298
00:17:46.984 --> 00:17:50.304
mesenchymal phenotype required for tumor progression?

299
00:17:51.144 --> 00:17:54.884
So we're asking also how intratumor heterogeneity

300
00:17:54.904 --> 00:17:57.544
emerges and what are the mechanisms that drive it.

301
00:17:58.004 --> 00:18:01.684
So in collaboration with the groups of Mayumi Ito and Markus Sauber, my colleagues

302
00:18:01.704 --> 00:18:05.224
at NYU, and our co-mentor student, Paola Angulo,

303
00:18:05.864 --> 00:18:09.564
we used this mouse model to study that question.

304
00:18:09.784 --> 00:18:11.884
Is important intratumor heterogeneity for

305
00:18:12.764 --> 00:18:16.144
tumor progression? So in this model, rather than

306
00:18:16.344 --> 00:18:20.244
activating the BRAF oncogene or deleting PTEN as we normally do

307
00:18:20.304 --> 00:18:23.524
from the tyrosinase promoter, we use the c-kit promoter.

308
00:18:23.554 --> 00:18:27.304
And the reason for this is because c-kit is expressed in the melanocyte stem

309
00:18:27.344 --> 00:18:30.724
cells, and we can synchronize,

310
00:18:31.644 --> 00:18:35.424
by targeting specifically these cells, the tumor cells are

311
00:18:35.484 --> 00:18:38.804
going to now migrate to the epidermis and then start

312
00:18:39.164 --> 00:18:42.204
proliferating and going downwards to the dermis.

313
00:18:42.224 --> 00:18:45.704
So this model really recapitulates the early stages of

314
00:18:45.904 --> 00:18:49.124
melanoma genesis with the epidermal to dermal

315
00:18:49.184 --> 00:18:51.084
invasion.So

316
00:18:52.044 --> 00:18:55.984
when we use this model and we first of all remove the

317
00:18:56.024 --> 00:18:59.024
hair, we treat the mice with 4-hydroxy-tamoxifen.

318
00:18:59.404 --> 00:19:03.364
We also use a lineage tracer that allows us to separate the tomato

319
00:19:03.424 --> 00:19:05.304
positive cells, which are the tumor cells.

320
00:19:05.884 --> 00:19:09.824
We collected tumors at two, four, and six weeks to conduct

321
00:19:10.584 --> 00:19:14.414
single cell RNA sequencing from the two fractions, the

322
00:19:14.524 --> 00:19:15.784
stromal cells and the

323
00:19:17.284 --> 00:19:21.044
tomato positive cancer cells. So immediately we can

324
00:19:21.084 --> 00:19:24.954
see that a progression of these

325
00:19:25.004 --> 00:19:28.904
tumors associates with emergence of intra-tumor heterogeneity as

326
00:19:28.964 --> 00:19:32.844
per this UMAP. I hope it's going to become more clear now if we look at the

327
00:19:32.864 --> 00:19:35.284
progression from zero to four and six weeks.

328
00:19:35.664 --> 00:19:39.424
You can see that initially the majority of the tumor is melanocytic, is

329
00:19:40.044 --> 00:19:43.744
mature or differentiated. But as we move to four weeks, we

330
00:19:43.824 --> 00:19:47.024
see more mesenchymal cells. We divided them

331
00:19:47.124 --> 00:19:50.944
into phenotypes to mesenchymal one and mesenchymal two,

332
00:19:51.604 --> 00:19:55.034
and also a population of neural crest-like cells

333
00:19:55.184 --> 00:19:59.044
emerges. And over time, the population of melanocytic cells

334
00:19:59.124 --> 00:20:02.924
is significantly reduced and these dedifferentiated cells take

335
00:20:03.004 --> 00:20:03.244
over.

336
00:20:04.384 --> 00:20:07.604
These signatures that we defined as melanocytic, neural crest,

337
00:20:07.904 --> 00:20:11.844
intermediate, or mesenchymal are very reminiscent of other

338
00:20:12.244 --> 00:20:15.084
similar signatures that have been previously reported in the field.

339
00:20:15.844 --> 00:20:19.584
What is remarkable, at least to me, is that in different

340
00:20:19.624 --> 00:20:23.144
mice we consistently see the same pattern of emergence of

341
00:20:23.164 --> 00:20:26.444
intra-tumor heterogeneity. It's really reproducible over

342
00:20:26.484 --> 00:20:29.404
time. And if we look at the

343
00:20:30.184 --> 00:20:33.944
tissue, you can see, for instance, here at this four-week time point,

344
00:20:34.524 --> 00:20:38.224
that the majority of the tumor cells that expressed Melan-A and

345
00:20:38.244 --> 00:20:41.324
therefore are more differentiated, stay

346
00:20:41.444 --> 00:20:44.804
compartmentalized in the epidermis, whereas the more

347
00:20:44.864 --> 00:20:48.644
undifferentiated PDGF-beta positive cells

348
00:20:48.744 --> 00:20:52.364
are in the dermis. Over time, these populations mix,

349
00:20:53.024 --> 00:20:55.614
and no longer remain compartmentalized.

350
00:20:56.184 --> 00:20:59.504
This compartmentalization suggests the possibility that the

351
00:20:59.564 --> 00:21:03.164
differentiation is a result of the crosstalk between the cancer

352
00:21:03.264 --> 00:21:05.624
cells and the microenvironment.

353
00:21:06.724 --> 00:21:09.624
Then we use a program called, or a

354
00:21:10.824 --> 00:21:14.524
software called SEINec, that allows us to predict

355
00:21:14.744 --> 00:21:18.464
the gene regulatory networks that are in control of these different,

356
00:21:19.984 --> 00:21:23.824
pathways of these different phenotypes, in this case, the mesenchymal one.

357
00:21:24.264 --> 00:21:27.284
And RUNX1 emerge as the most significantly

358
00:21:27.344 --> 00:21:31.104
upregulated signature of this most important

359
00:21:31.204 --> 00:21:33.204
gene regulatory network in these

360
00:21:34.144 --> 00:21:35.364
mesenchymal cells.

361
00:21:36.324 --> 00:21:40.204
Also we saw NR2F2 to be also upregulated, and this is

362
00:21:40.264 --> 00:21:40.904
another

363
00:21:41.784 --> 00:21:45.604
gene regulatory network that we have seen associated with mesenchymal

364
00:21:45.644 --> 00:21:49.504
differentiation previously. So if we cross these mice with RUNX1 flox

365
00:21:49.564 --> 00:21:49.904
mice,

366
00:21:50.924 --> 00:21:54.754
we can investigate if RUNX require for the establishment

367
00:21:54.844 --> 00:21:58.784
of differentiation. And I hope you can see that in this upper tumor, again, we

368
00:21:58.824 --> 00:22:02.264
can see the separation between the melanocytic

369
00:22:02.304 --> 00:22:05.684
population, and these are very thick tumors at four weeks.

370
00:22:06.064 --> 00:22:09.924
However, if we cross these mice with RUNX1, you no longer

371
00:22:10.004 --> 00:22:13.673
see these thick tumors. They're much thinner, and the majority of the

372
00:22:13.744 --> 00:22:16.744
tumor remains in the melanocytic state.

373
00:22:17.364 --> 00:22:20.984
So this demonstrates that RUNX1 is required for the emergence of

374
00:22:21.064 --> 00:22:24.584
intra-tumor heterogeneity, and we have found with different epigenomic

375
00:22:24.624 --> 00:22:28.464
analyses that RUNX1 controls an entire signature of genes

376
00:22:28.484 --> 00:22:32.424
required for mesenchymal and neural crest-like differentiation, including, for

377
00:22:32.484 --> 00:22:33.624
instance, NGFR.

378
00:22:35.044 --> 00:22:38.024
So moving now quickly to the other end of the

379
00:22:38.644 --> 00:22:42.564
metastasis process, we can move now to metastasis in the brain,

380
00:22:42.624 --> 00:22:46.384
brain metastasis, which is really, unfortunately, a frequent

381
00:22:46.424 --> 00:22:50.304
occurrence in melanoma, and sometimes these tumors are

382
00:22:50.804 --> 00:22:52.764
not responsive to checkpoint blockade.

383
00:22:52.824 --> 00:22:56.673
So the field has a lot of progress in investigating the mechanisms that

384
00:22:56.704 --> 00:23:00.134
drive tropism of melanoma cells to the brain, and these

385
00:23:00.184 --> 00:23:02.844
include PI3 kinase activity

386
00:23:03.664 --> 00:23:07.624
signaling. Increased chromosomal instability has been also shown to promote

387
00:23:07.643 --> 00:23:11.284
brain metastasis. Addition molecules like L-1CAM,

388
00:23:12.004 --> 00:23:15.564
neural-like features or programs have been shown also by my group and

389
00:23:15.624 --> 00:23:17.964
others to contribute to brain metastasis.

390
00:23:18.364 --> 00:23:22.344
Metabolic adaptations of the serine and glycine pathway, but also more

391
00:23:22.384 --> 00:23:24.584
importantly, reliance on OXPHOS.

392
00:23:24.944 --> 00:23:28.844
The melanoma cells that metastasize to the brain seem to

393
00:23:28.904 --> 00:23:32.164
have increased dependence on mitochondrial metabolism.

394
00:23:32.584 --> 00:23:35.944
We saw that previously in a study published a few years ago.

395
00:23:35.984 --> 00:23:39.884
We found that the mitochondria from the brain metastasis

396
00:23:40.324 --> 00:23:43.784
were elongated compared to the corresponding mitochondria of the same

397
00:23:43.884 --> 00:23:45.824
patient's intracranial metastasis.

398
00:23:46.404 --> 00:23:50.144
We found also that these brain metastasis have increased

399
00:23:50.224 --> 00:23:53.184
oxygen consumption rate compared to their counterparts.

400
00:23:53.364 --> 00:23:57.024
So this reliance on OXPHOS creates an Achilles heel

401
00:23:57.364 --> 00:24:01.004
that is waiting to be exploited. So Maria, a

402
00:24:01.064 --> 00:24:04.484
postdoc in the lab, and Ali, a grad student,

403
00:24:05.284 --> 00:24:08.904
conducted a comparison of proteomic and transcriptomic

404
00:24:08.964 --> 00:24:12.824
profiling and found that a lot of the proteins that are upregulated

405
00:24:12.884 --> 00:24:16.764
in brain metastasis include mitochondrial genes or genes

406
00:24:16.824 --> 00:24:20.644
involved in mitochondrial respiration, including CNDP1.

407
00:24:21.124 --> 00:24:24.584
So it's associated with poor prognosis and is upregulated in brain

408
00:24:24.624 --> 00:24:28.114
metastasis not only of melanoma but also of breast cancer.

409
00:24:28.744 --> 00:24:32.564
So CNDP1 is a dipeptidase that cleaves carnosine, a very abundant

410
00:24:33.224 --> 00:24:37.144
metabolite in the brain. And the hypothesis was that as

411
00:24:37.164 --> 00:24:39.094
the cells arrive to the brain, they have to

412
00:24:40.124 --> 00:24:43.984
upregulate CNDP1 to cleave carnosine and

413
00:24:44.024 --> 00:24:47.044
eliminate this highly abundant metabolite that is

414
00:24:47.124 --> 00:24:51.084
anti-tumorality in the brain. We found that CNDP1

415
00:24:51.104 --> 00:24:54.904
levels were upregulated progressively from extracranial to cranial

416
00:24:54.944 --> 00:24:58.864
metastasis, that when we silence CNDP1, we see

417
00:24:58.984 --> 00:25:02.024
a dramatic reduction of brain metastasis

418
00:25:03.004 --> 00:25:05.663
in different models. I'm just showing one of them.

419
00:25:06.114 --> 00:25:10.044
And also in already established metastasis, if we induce the silencing of

420
00:25:10.084 --> 00:25:13.884
CNDP1, we can interfere, we can block the further progression of brain

421
00:25:13.924 --> 00:25:17.524
metastasis. Conversely, in collaboration with a group of Sherry

422
00:25:17.564 --> 00:25:21.312
Holdman, we found that the overexpression of CNDP1-In

423
00:25:21.512 --> 00:25:25.352
a very poorly metastatic model, significantly enhances

424
00:25:25.412 --> 00:25:29.132
brain metastases similarly to another protein that she had found

425
00:25:29.152 --> 00:25:32.552
previously to also promote brain metastases.

426
00:25:32.882 --> 00:25:36.492
And is particularly observed in brain metastases, and it doesn't

427
00:25:36.552 --> 00:25:38.272
promote metastases to other sites.

428
00:25:38.932 --> 00:25:42.912
Silencing of CNTP1 reduces the number of mitochondria per

429
00:25:42.992 --> 00:25:45.452
cell, increases the number of

430
00:25:46.452 --> 00:25:50.412
evacuated mitochondria, reduces the number

431
00:25:50.552 --> 00:25:54.492
of TCA intermediates, suggesting that the mitochondria is not working

432
00:25:54.552 --> 00:25:58.522
properly, and also it reduces oxygen consumption

433
00:25:58.632 --> 00:26:01.612
rate as well as increase in ROS.

434
00:26:02.252 --> 00:26:05.872
So to conclude this model, we suggest

435
00:26:06.072 --> 00:26:09.052
that the upregulation of CNTP1 protects

436
00:26:09.552 --> 00:26:13.322
brain metastasis cells, and that the

437
00:26:13.392 --> 00:26:17.012
targeting of CNTP1 leads to accumulation of carnosine that now

438
00:26:17.212 --> 00:26:20.842
acts as a ionophore that brings copper inside the mitochondria,

439
00:26:21.232 --> 00:26:24.812
induces the production of reactive oxygen species, and the

440
00:26:24.832 --> 00:26:27.332
degradation of important proteins for the mitochondria.

441
00:26:28.652 --> 00:26:32.552
We don't have much more time, but I just wanted to indicate that we know

442
00:26:32.712 --> 00:26:36.412
CNTP1 also can cleave another metabolite in the brain,

443
00:26:36.652 --> 00:26:39.272
homocarnosine, into L-histidine and GABA.

444
00:26:39.812 --> 00:26:43.772
We found that the silencing of CNTP1 reduces the expression of

445
00:26:43.832 --> 00:26:44.492
GABAergic

446
00:26:45.392 --> 00:26:48.852
signaling, and particularly the expression of GABA

447
00:26:48.892 --> 00:26:52.392
receptors. And this brought us to look at the potential

448
00:26:52.452 --> 00:26:55.872
interactions between the cancer cells and the neurons.

449
00:26:56.232 --> 00:27:00.192
We saw the presence of synapses in the proximity within the

450
00:27:00.212 --> 00:27:02.492
cancer cells and the axons of neurons.

451
00:27:03.002 --> 00:27:06.992
And we have done some electrophysiology analysis that suggests that the

452
00:27:07.052 --> 00:27:10.612
homocarnosine, that is the substrate of CNTP1,

453
00:27:10.932 --> 00:27:14.452
contributes to electrical signaling in the brain microenvironment.

454
00:27:14.952 --> 00:27:18.692
So this suggests that CNTP1 not only shields the cancer

455
00:27:18.812 --> 00:27:22.632
cells from metabolic stress, but also can contribute

456
00:27:22.652 --> 00:27:25.192
to this tumor-neural metabolic competition.

457
00:27:25.272 --> 00:27:28.012
Of course, these are not the only mechanisms.

458
00:27:28.192 --> 00:27:31.492
In recent years, there has been really an explosion of studies

459
00:27:33.212 --> 00:27:36.912
demonstrating different mechanisms by which the cancer cells

460
00:27:36.952 --> 00:27:40.732
interact with the microglia, with the astrocytes, and how they

461
00:27:40.772 --> 00:27:44.652
hijack this stromal microenvironment to their benefit.

462
00:27:45.252 --> 00:27:48.852
I hope I have convinced you that all these adaptations that cancer cells

463
00:27:48.992 --> 00:27:52.392
undergo in the primary site or in distal sites,

464
00:27:52.912 --> 00:27:55.812
they can also be targetable dependencies.

465
00:27:56.152 --> 00:28:00.012
So one could envision the possibility of targeting physical states by

466
00:28:00.052 --> 00:28:03.752
blocking chromatin hubs to prevent the initial dissemination.

467
00:28:03.772 --> 00:28:07.292
We could reprogram the disease-associated or

468
00:28:07.312 --> 00:28:11.012
Alzheimer's-like microglia to enhance response to

469
00:28:11.232 --> 00:28:14.452
checkpoint blockade, or we can target this dependency of

470
00:28:14.512 --> 00:28:15.572
OXPHOS.

471
00:28:16.632 --> 00:28:17.092
With that,

472
00:28:17.912 --> 00:28:21.752
I want to indicate that the same barriers that cancer

473
00:28:21.812 --> 00:28:25.152
cells overcome during this process are also the

474
00:28:25.252 --> 00:28:28.912
architects of its own targeted vulnerabilities.

475
00:28:29.472 --> 00:28:32.612
With that, I want to thank all the members of the lab who have contributed to these

476
00:28:32.732 --> 00:28:33.232
studies.

477
00:28:34.552 --> 00:28:35.352
It doesn't move anymore.

478
00:28:36.552 --> 00:28:40.452
And particularly, I want to thank my collaborators

